{:proof/problem-id "apm-a98J02", :proof/classification :partial, :proof/output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (absolutely continuous \\(f:[0,1]\\to\\mathbb R\\), derivative in \\(L^2\\), quadratic difference quotient, ε–δ goal) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (the Lean target concludes the small-quotient property; it isn’t assumed) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (even standalone, it’s a concrete modulus-of-continuity theorem for \\(L^2\\) derivatives) · notes: helper lemma isolates the localized Cauchy–Schwarz estimate that drives both the informal and Lean proofs.\n\n```clojure\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Show that an absolutely continuous f with square-integrable derivative has small quadratic difference quotients on short intervals.\"\n :terms [{:name \"FTC for AC functions\"\n          :meaning \"Absolute continuity gives f(x)-f(y)=int_y^x f'(t) dt.\"\n          :needed-because \"Turns pointwise differences into integrals of f'.\"}\n         {:name \"localized Cauchy-Schwarz\"\n          :meaning \"|int_y^x f'|^2 <= (x-y) int_y^x |f'|^2.\"\n          :needed-because \"Connects the desired quotient with int |f'|^2 on the same interval.\"}\n         {:name \"absolute continuity of the |f'|^2 integral\"\n          :meaning \"Because |f'|^2 lies in L^1([0,1]), integrating it over sets of small measure gives a small result.\"\n          :needed-because \"Provides the δ(ε) after the Cauchy-Schwarz reduction.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"FTC for AC\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 relation f(x)-f(y)=integral of f'\"\n             :why-this-now \"Reduces the statement to estimates on f'.\"\n             :lean-target \"ac_increment_as_integral\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Use `intervalIntegral.deriv_eq_sub`.\"}\n            {:id :s2\n             :formal-dependency \"Cauchy-Schwarz\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Output of :s1\"\n             :why-this-now \"Bounds |f(x)-f(y)|^2/(x-y) by int_y^x |f'|^2.\"\n             :lean-target \"cauchy_schwarz_local\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Standard inequality already available.\"}\n            {:id :s3\n             :formal-dependency \"integral_small_on_short_interval\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Bound from :s2\"\n             :why-this-now \"Use integrability of |f'|^2 to choose δ so that every interval of length < δ has integral < ε.\"\n             :lean-target \"L2_integral_small_on_short_interval\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Follows from absolute continuity of Lebesgue measure on [0,1].\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```clojure\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"If f:[0,1]->Real is absolutely continuous with derivative in L^2, then |f(x)-f(y)|^2/(x-y) can be made arbitrarily small whenever x-y is small.\"\n             :formal-name \"l2_difference_quotient_small\"\n             :formal-target \"forall f : Real -> Real,\n  AbsolutelyContinuousOn f (Set.Icc 0 1) ->\n  HasFiniteIntegral (fun x => (deriv f x)^2) (Measure.restrict Lebesgue (Set.Icc 0 1)) ->\n  forall eps > 0, exists delta > 0, forall {x y}, 0 <= y ∧ y < x ∧ x <= 1 ∧ x - y < delta ->\n    (|f x - f y|^2) / (x - y) < eps.\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"Captures the sought uniform control on the quadratic difference quotient.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"l2_difference_quotient_small\"\n              :formal-statement \"same as formal-target\"\n              :informal-clause \"Main statement.\"\n              :role :main-theorem}\n             {:formal-name \"cauchy_schwarz_interval\"\n              :formal-statement \"forall 0 <= y < x <= 1 and integrable g, |integral g from y to x|^2 <= (x-y) * integral |g|^2 from y to x.\"\n              :informal-clause \"Bridge from differences to L^2 control.\"\n              :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Why it’s hard.**  Absolute continuity already gives uniform continuity, so it’s tempting to stop there. But the problem wants the *quadratic* difference quotient \\(|f(x)-f(y)|^2/(x-y)\\) to be uniformly small, which is stronger and false for a generic absolutely continuous function. The missing ingredient is the extra \\(L^2\\)-control on \\(f'\\); until you exploit that, the \\(\\varepsilon\\)–\\(\\delta\\) goal looks mysterious.\n\n**The key insight.**  Undo the fundamental theorem of calculus to write\n\\[\nf(x)-f(y)=\\int_y^x f'(t)\\,dt,\n\\]\nthen apply Cauchy–Schwarz on \\((y,x)\\) to get\n\\[\n\\frac{|f(x)-f(y)|^2}{x-y}\\le \\int_y^x |f'(t)|^2\\,dt.\n\\]\nBecause \\(|f'|^2\\in L^1([0,1])\\), the last integral is an *absolutely continuous* function of the interval, so it becomes \\(<\\varepsilon\\) whenever the interval length is \\(<\\delta(\\varepsilon)\\).\n\n**Complete proof.**  \nFix \\(\\varepsilon>0\\). Since \\(|f'|^2\\in L^1([0,1])\\), there exists \\(\\delta>0\\) such that any measurable \\(A\\subset[0,1]\\) with Lebesgue measure \\(m(A)<\\delta\\) satisfies \\(\\int_A |f'|^2<\\varepsilon\\) (absolute continuity of the Lebesgue integral on finite measure spaces). Take \\(0\\le y<x\\le 1\\) with \\(x-y<\\delta\\). Because \\(f\\) is absolutely continuous,\n\\[\nf(x)-f(y)=\\int_y^x f'(t)\\,dt.\n\\]\nCauchy–Schwarz gives\n\\[\n|f(x)-f(y)|^2 \\le (x-y)\\int_y^x |f'(t)|^2\\,dt.\n\\]\nDividing by \\(x-y>0\\) yields\n\\[\n\\frac{|f(x)-f(y)|^2}{x-y}\\le \\int_y^x |f'(t)|^2\\,dt <\\varepsilon\n\\]\n(the last inequality uses that \\((y,x)\\) has length \\(<\\delta\\)). This proves the desired uniform estimate.\n\n**Lean 4 formalization.**  \n- Artifacts populated: `proof-plan.edn`, `formal-alignment.edn`, `execute.md`, and `changelog.edn` under `/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a98J02/apm-v2-a98J02-1775004665812/`.\n- Plan: show \\(f(x)-f(y)\\) is an interval integral (`intervalIntegral.deriv_eq_sub`), apply Cauchy–Schwarz to bound the quotient by \\(\\int_y^x |f'|^2\\), then prove that these integrals go to zero uniformly as the interval length shrinks.\n- Progress: the first two steps are routine in Mathlib; the remaining obstacle is step (3). Mathlib lacks a convenient lemma stating “if \\(g\\in L^1([0,1])\\), then for every \\(\\varepsilon>0\\) there exists \\(\\delta>0\\) such that \\(|b-a|<\\delta\\Rightarrow\\int_a^b |g|<\\varepsilon\\).” Implementing this would require building the signed measure associated with \\(|f'|^2\\) and proving its absolute continuity explicitly. Because that machinery is nontrivial boilerplate, `Main.lean` still contains only the module header while this lemma is pending; once supplied (either upstream or locally), the formal proof can be completed and `lake build` run.\n\n**What connects.**  This technique—combine the fundamental theorem of calculus with a Hilbert-space inequality and the absolute continuity of an \\(L^1\\) integral—is the standard way to derive Morrey-type estimates. It shows up in Sobolev embeddings (\\(W^{1,2}\\subset C^{0,1/2}\\) in one dimension), in energy estimates for PDEs (where \\(L^2\\) control of the gradient gives Hölder continuity), and whenever you need a modulus of continuity from square-integrable derivatives. Keeping this “FTC + Cauchy–Schwarz + absolute continuity” template in your toolkit pays dividends across analysis prelims.", :proof/extraction {:phases {}, :dependency-graph nil, :arse-questions nil, :classification :partial, :phase-count 0, :dep-graph-count 0, :arse-count 0}, :proof/frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A98J02/Apm_v2_a98J02_1775004665812", :frame/id "apm-v2-a98J02-1775004665812", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :workspace/generated-at "2026-04-01T00:51:05.836883Z", :frame/shared-extension-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Local", :frame/module-root "ApmCana